r than peaceful norms of conflict resolution, are responsible for inhibiting the quick resort to violence in democratic polities. Rousseau finds that conflicts evolve through successive stages and that the constraining power of participatory institutions can vary across these stages. Finally, he demonstrates how constraint within states encourages the rise of clusters of democratic states that resemble "zones of peace" within the anarchic international structure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aDemocracy. 0aWarxPolitical aspectsvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476751440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767514/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles